{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584676","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584676"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:53:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:53:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14771"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14771"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.05,0.1,0,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7462"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65391"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7462"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14771"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50830"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5113"},{"type":"tags","id":"5155"},{"type":"tags","id":"10164"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18270"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21744"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65391"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EVitamin D analogues are commonly used as topical treatments for plaque psoriasis, a chronic inflammatory skin condition characterised by well-demarcated, erythematous plaques with silvery scale.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the therapeutic mechanism of vitamin D analogues in psoriasis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces keratinocyte proliferation and promotes normal differentiation","Causes keratinocyte destruction","Increases melanin production","Enhances skin barrier function only","Promotes keratinocyte proliferation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary mechanism of vitamin D analogues in psoriasis involves \u003Cstrong\u003Ereducing keratinocyte proliferation and promoting normal differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E. They bind to vitamin D receptors in skin cells, normalising the accelerated keratinocyte turnover that characterises psoriasis while also suppressing inflammatory mediators. By normalising keratinocyte function and reducing inflammation, vitamin D analogues help resolve the characteristic scaling and thickening of psoriatic plaques.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVitamin D analogues regulate cell growth and differentiation rather than destroying cells through \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratinocyte destruction. \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile vitamin D has effects on melanocytes, an \u003Cstrong\u003Eincrease in melanin production\u003C/strong\u003E is not the therapeutic mechanism for psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBarrier function may improve with vitamin D analogues\u003C/strong\u003E; however, this effect is secondary to the main effects on keratinocyte regulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that vitamin D analogues \u003Cstrong\u003Epromote\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratinocyte proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as this would worsen rather than improve psoriasis. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin D analogues reduce keratinocyte proliferation and promote normal differentiation in psoriasis","Topical vitamin D analogues work by binding to vitamin D receptors in skin cells to reduce inflammation","Vitamin D analogues are effective first-line treatments for mild-moderate plaque psoriasis"],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50830"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14771"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50830","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50830"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T13:16:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T09:39:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7462"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65391"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},